> You might think of it as an example, same as the `hello' package.
Solaris:
#!/usr/bin/sh
#	Copyright (c) 1984, 1986, 1987, 1988, 1989 AT&T
#	  All Rights Reserved
#	THIS IS UNPUBLISHED PROPRIETARY SOURCE CODE OF AT&T
#	The copyright notice above does not evidence any
#	actual or intended publication of such source code.
#ident	"@(#)false.sh	1.6	93/01/11 SMI"	/* SVr4.0 1.3	*/
[obvious invocation of exit snipped to avoid lawsuit. Yup, *1* line.]
At least /bin/false on the Linux box doesn't start with pompous legalese
(unusual for GNU stuff, but I guess that even RMS had enough sense not to
toss GPL over the usage of exit). 
